    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-14T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="971"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d971">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/6–1454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Saigon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MR2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McClintock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-14T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 14, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2770. Repeated information Paris priority 985, Geneva 232. After the exiguous
                    diplomatic corps of Saigon, numbered six in all, presented <persName
                        corresp="#p_DM1">DeJean</persName> with a silver pot this evening, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DM1">DeJean</persName> requested me to join him in his office to
                    read an urgent top secret telegram addressed to <persName corresp="#p_EGP1"
                        >General Ely</persName> from <persName corresp="#p_VGJE1">General
                        Valluy</persName>.</p>
                <p>This telegram represents <persName corresp="#p_RAAW1">Admiral Radford</persName>
                    as insisting on utility of bringing three Korean divisions for fighting in
                    Indochina and as adding (which I told <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >DeJean</persName> would be manifest impossibility) US Naval lift could
                    accomplish transport of all three divisions to this theater within one week.</p>
                <p>I told <persName corresp="#p_DM1">DeJean</persName> that Department had kindly
                    given me some background on this problem (Department telegram 2551, repeated
                    Geneva <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 178, Paris 4476)<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d971fn1">Telegram <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 178 to
                        Geneva. June 9, repeated to Paris as 4476 and to Saigon as 2551, summarized
                        a conversation of the same day between Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> and French Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BH1"
                            >Bonnet</persName> concerning the possible participation of U.S. armed
                        forces in Indochina. For text of <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss>
                        178, see <ref target="frus1952-54v16#pg_1100">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >xvi</hi>, p. 1100</ref>.</note> and gave <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >DeJean</persName> a verbal paraphrase of what Secretary had told <persName
                        corresp="#p_BH1">Bonnet.</persName> I likewise outlined in brief conditions
                    precedent which US had wisely laid down in discussions between Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_LJ1"
                        >Laniel</persName>. I said I thought that until French formed government it
                    was unnecessary to get excited about Korean or any other divisions since the
                    Secretary’s conditions had yet to be fulfilled.</p>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Re training aspects of overall problem, I observed to <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >DeJean</persName> that we had not received any request from French
                    Government for assistance in this regard and that although I much admired energy
                    and desire to be ahead of time of <persName corresp="#p_ODLGJW1">General
                        O’Daniel</persName>, I had told him that we <pb facs="0310" n="1692"
                        xml:id="pg_1692"/> would not undertake training mission until <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGP1">General Ely</persName>’s own conditions in this respect
                    had been met; namely, that training program was but one phase of overall
                    integrated program.</p>
                <p>I asked <persName corresp="#p_DM1">DeJean</persName> to arrange interview
                    tomorrow for me with himself and <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>.
                    This pleased former Commissioner General very much, and I shall be glad to meet
                    with both French representatives as <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                    >DeJean</persName>’s presence will not make <persName corresp="#p_EGP1"
                        >Ely</persName> less a General nor <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >DeJean</persName> less a diplomat.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MR2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McClintock</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
